<DOC><DOCNO> AP900717-0069 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-17-90 1227EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Britain-Drugs     07-17 0155</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Britain-Drugs,0159</SECOND><HEAD>International Police Operation Nets Major Drug Bust</HEAD><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A police operation involving French, Dutch andBritish officers has netted Britain's largest haul of amphetaminesulphate, the drug known as ``speed,'' police said Tuesday.   Eleven men were arrested Monday when police and customs officersraided a boat at the mouth of the Thames River, 40 miles east ofLondon, Kent police said.   Police fired a stun grenade but no one was injured in the raid,which recovered 132 pounds of the drug worth up to $18 million,said Kent police Chief Inspector Alan Butterfield.   Five of the men were arrested as they unloaded the motorcruiser, Merulius, which had sailed from Holland on Friday undersurveillance by coast guard vessels, police said.   Customs officers and police arrested six other people in London.The arrests capped a three-month investigation, code-namedOperation Tributary. Butterfield called it the largest seizure everin Great Britain.</TEXT></DOC>